  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, although they are more commonly associated with aging. When cataracts develop in individuals under the age of 40, they are often referred to as **\"juvenile cataracts.\"** These early-onset cataracts can arise from a variety of causes, which differ from the age-related factors typically seen in older adults. Here are some of the most common causes of cataracts in younger individuals:\n\n1. **Congenital (Present at Birth) and Developmental Cataracts:**\n   - **Genetic Factors:** Inherited genetic mutations can lead to cataract formation in infants and young children.\n   - **Intrauterine Infections:** Infections such as rubella, toxoplasmosis, or cytomegalovirus during pregnancy can result in cataracts in the developing fetus.\n   - **Metabolic Disorders:** Conditions like galactosemia can interfere with normal lens development.\n\n2. **Trauma:**\n   - **Eye Injuries:** Physical injuries to the eye, whether from accidents, sports, or other causes, can damage the lens and lead to cataract formation, sometimes years after the injury.\n\n3. **Systemic Diseases:**\n   - **Diabetes:** High blood sugar levels associated with diabetes can increase the risk of cataract development at a younger age.\n   - **Other Chronic Conditions:** Diseases such as myotonic dystrophy or atopic dermatitis have been linked to earlier onset of cataracts.\n\n4. **Prolonged Use of Certain Medications:**\n   - **Corticosteroids:** Long-term use of steroid medications, whether systemic or topical (e.g., eye drops), can contribute to cataract formation.\n   - **Other Medications:** Some anticonvulsants and other drugs have been associated with an increased risk of cataracts.\n\n5. **Radiation Exposure:**\n   - **Ultraviolet Light:** Excessive exposure to UV radiation from the sun or from artificial sources can damage the lens over time.\n   - **Radiation Therapy:** Treatment for cancers in the head and neck area can increase the likelihood of cataracts in the exposed eye.\n\n6. **Lifestyle Factors:**\n   - **Smoking and Alcohol Use:** Both have been linked to an increased risk of cataracts, potentially affecting individuals at a younger age.\n   - **Poor Nutrition:** Deficiencies in certain vitamins and antioxidants may contribute to lens clouding.\n\n7. **Other Eye Conditions:**\n   - **Uveitis:** Chronic inflammation of the middle layer of the eye can lead to cataract formation.\n   - **Retinitis Pigmentosa:** A group of genetic disorders that affect the retina and can be associated with early cataract development.\n\n**Symptoms of Cataracts in Younger Individuals:**\n- Blurred or cloudy vision\n- Increased sensitivity to glare\n- Frequent changes in eyeglass or contact lens prescriptions\n- Difficulty seeing in low light or at night\n- Fading or yellowing of colors\n\n**Management and Treatment:**\nIf a young person is diagnosed with cataracts, it's essential to consult with an ophthalmologist to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment. In many cases, especially when cataracts significantly impair vision or daily activities, surgical removal of the cloudy lens and replacement with an artificial intraocular lens (IOL) may be recommended.\n\n**Prevention Tips:**\nWhile not all causes of cataracts are preventable, certain measures can reduce the risk:\n- Protecting eyes from excessive UV radiation by wearing sunglasses that block 100% of UVA and UVB rays.\n- Maintaining good control of systemic conditions like diabetes.\n- Avoiding smoking and limiting alcohol consumption.\n- Wearing protective eyewear during activities that pose a risk of eye injury.\n- Maintaining a healthy diet rich in antioxidants and essential vitamins.\n\nIn summary, although cataracts are typically associated with aging, various factors can lead to their development in younger individuals. Early detection and appropriate management are crucial to preserving vision and quality of life.",
